1
00:00:01,633 --> 00:00:27,472
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhodassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhodassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhodassa

2
00:00:27,942 --> 00:00:32,167
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble, and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:34,651 --> 00:00:46,345
So this evening, to carry on our little Dharma exploration, Dharma Pada exploration, thought I'd choose verse number 46.

4
00:00:46,386 --> 00:00:50,411
I shall chant it in the Pali first.

5
00:00:51,813 --> 00:00:54,777
PENU PAMANG KAYANG IMMA

6
00:00:55,195 --> 00:01:14,688
And the translation.

7
00:01:16,542 --> 00:01:18,245
This is Jill Fronsdale.

8
00:01:18,867 --> 00:01:29,468
Knowing this body is like foam, fully awake to its mirage-like image, cutting off Mara's flowers, one goes unseen by the king of death.

9
00:01:30,751 --> 00:01:35,260
And a slightly, I prefer Tanisaro's translation actually on this one.

10
00:01:35,780 --> 00:01:55,998
knowing this body is like foam realizing its nature a mirage cutting out the blossoms of mara you go where the king of death can't see that's a bit more dramatic i think so let me read a little story that comes with it

11
00:02:05,058 --> 00:02:18,758
On one occasion, the Buddha was residing at Jetavana Monastery in Savatthi, and a certain Bhikkhu, after obtaining a subject of meditation from the Buddha, went to the forest for the purpose of practicing meditation.

12
00:02:19,459 --> 00:02:25,867
Although he strove diligently, he made little progress and was not happy with himself, and so he thought,

13
00:02:25,848 --> 00:02:51,837
i'll return to jetavana monastery and request the enlightened one to give me another subject of meditation better suited to my temperament and with this thought he set out to return to savati now on the way he saw a mirage reflecting mindfully within himself he realized that a mirage after all is only an illusion caused by a sheet of water vapor

14
00:02:52,561 --> 00:02:59,068
So also was his body an illusion and insubstantial by reason of birth and decay.

15
00:02:59,128 --> 00:03:05,355
And fixing his mind on the mirage, he continued with this meditation practice.

16
00:03:05,376 --> 00:03:11,181
Later, he went for a bath near the bank of the river Achiravati.

17
00:03:11,983 --> 00:03:20,592
While resting under a tree close to the river and seeing the froth breaking up, he realized further the impermanent nature of the body.

18
00:03:21,467 --> 00:03:30,801
Now from Jetavana Monastery, the Buddha saw the Bhikkhu and sent forth his radiance and exhorted him, Bhikkhu, you are on the right track.

19
00:03:31,102 --> 00:03:31,663
Keep it up.

20
00:03:32,144 --> 00:03:38,633
It is good that you've realized the body is impermanent like froth and insubstantial like a mirage.

21
00:03:39,634 --> 00:03:44,322
At the conclusion of the exhortation, the Bhikkhu attained Arahatship.

22
00:03:45,484 --> 00:03:46,384
Well, that's not bad, is it?

23
00:03:47,888 --> 00:03:50,731
See what we're missing out on, not being born at the time of the Buddha.

24
00:03:54,965 --> 00:04:04,854
So knowing this body is like foam, realizing its nature a mirage, cutting out the blossoms of Mara, you go to where the king of death can't see.

25
00:04:05,635 --> 00:04:07,197
So a couple of vocabs there.

26
00:04:08,899 --> 00:04:11,401
Miraci just means to shimmer or glitter.

27
00:04:11,442 --> 00:04:13,864
And so it becomes a word for mirage.

28
00:04:14,384 --> 00:04:17,266
And that is a metaphor for illusion.

29
00:04:17,288 --> 00:04:21,951
If you see it as a mirage, that it is a mirage, it's an illusion.

30
00:04:22,151 --> 00:04:24,735
But if you think it's real, then it's a delusion.

31
00:04:26,757 --> 00:04:40,901
the um now here it says uh having cut off mara's flower-tipped arrows that's a more direct translation having cut off mara's flower-tipped arrows

32
00:04:43,125 --> 00:05:10,095
so now it's interesting because the only time that i'm certain that the arrows of mara approached the buddha was just before he was fully liberated and uh it attacked him with you know um what about the sensual life it's great out there what are you doing just sitting under this tree and then there was fear fear of failure and who was he anyway to try and become fully liberated etc etc

33
00:05:10,074 --> 00:05:21,690
And as these arrows came to the Buddha, because of his determination, commitment to his path and that sense of hope, they turned into flowers.

34
00:05:24,053 --> 00:05:30,041
So here, I think this Mara's flower-tipped arrows is sort of extending the metaphor a bit.

35
00:05:31,084 --> 00:05:34,129
because flowers stands for sensual pleasure.

36
00:05:34,610 --> 00:05:37,052
So he cut off sensual pleasure.

37
00:05:37,333 --> 00:05:46,345
So there are three things in this discourse, insubstantiality, impermanence, and of course the cause of suffering, attachment.

38
00:05:48,468 --> 00:05:51,612
And the last thing is, oh yeah, the king of death.

39
00:05:51,911 --> 00:05:55,737
So if he's gone beyond the king of death, then of course he must be liberated.

40
00:05:56,338 --> 00:05:59,521
That's just another way of saying that the person's liberated.

41
00:06:03,315 --> 00:06:22,523
so um when we're contemplating the body as body there are these three characteristics to look at so this impermanence of the body i mean that's pretty easy for us to see the older we get it's just things things change uh

42
00:06:22,502 --> 00:06:51,682
uh of downwardly uh but um so that's not so uh important that's not so difficult for us to see but we don't really see the power of seeing impermanence when unless somebody dies so even today i was talking to somebody a student who is having sort of problems with seeing impermanence everywhere it's coming up as a lot of fear and they've had two close deaths in the family one after the other very sudden

43
00:06:51,663 --> 00:07:14,396
so uh when that happens of course the impermanence of the body becomes quite real it's in substantiality it's fragility you know we're all living on a on a knife edge and the the image there is of the of froth on water it just breaks up you've seen it sort of gathering on streams you know

44
00:07:14,377 --> 00:07:16,720
And then it just breaks away, breaks up.

45
00:07:16,819 --> 00:07:21,286
So it's the whole deconstruction of the body.

46
00:07:22,026 --> 00:07:33,802
If you were to imagine it laid out before you, all the bits and pieces, then we would see that it's just something that's constructed, something that's put together.

47
00:07:34,069 --> 00:07:37,754
But of course, it's real in the sense that we feel it.

48
00:07:38,274 --> 00:07:42,098
You bite your tongue and you can't deny that you have a body.

49
00:07:43,338 --> 00:07:45,762
It definitely feels real.

50
00:07:46,382 --> 00:07:49,966
But of course, that is the perception that we are trying to cut through.

51
00:07:49,985 --> 00:07:52,208
Pain is pain, that's fine.

52
00:07:52,728 --> 00:08:00,516
But when it's my pain, when I'm suffering from it, then it gives it a sense of reality, which it doesn't have.

53
00:08:01,980 --> 00:08:17,108
And it's interesting that the discourse uses the idea of vapor that's creating the mirage, the froth on the water, because the body, it seems, is 60% water.

54
00:08:17,749 --> 00:08:26,605
So if you were to separate all the elements of the body rather than the parts, you'd end up with a lot of bottles of water.

55
00:08:29,706 --> 00:08:48,677
And then when it comes to the body itself in terms of the attachment to the body, the main thing is, of course, our attachment to the body is something which is, we can't say beautiful for most of us because we have this awful image of

56
00:08:49,028 --> 00:08:53,774
of Hollywood, Bollywood, and CGI.

57
00:08:54,455 --> 00:08:57,138
You know, it's like nobody lives up to that standard.

58
00:08:57,879 --> 00:09:16,942
But there is always that, we can say, slight, well, obsession may be not so important, not so right a word, but definitely a concern that people see us as a pleasant, as pleasant, something to look at which is pleasant.

59
00:09:18,931 --> 00:09:22,096
And so there is this concern about how we look.

60
00:09:23,258 --> 00:09:36,940
And if a person is using their looks in order to gain advantage, of course, then you very quickly catch somebody who is attracted to you.

61
00:09:37,678 --> 00:09:52,532
and and and with that there comes power but there's also a real bite back it's not a feedback it's a bite back because now your sense of power is dependent on their admiration

62
00:09:53,001 --> 00:10:08,006
and of course when their admiration fades away you you you discover it's not love and of course if their admiration turns to somebody else then we're fired up with rage and jealousy so

63
00:10:08,273 --> 00:10:23,471
So there's a whole mixture of suffering that comes with being too concerned about how we look and sort of a distinction between cleanliness, tidiness, and beauty.

64
00:10:25,914 --> 00:10:35,225
So how do we overcome this connection to the body, the body as something that has to be beautiful in other people's eyes, you know?

65
00:10:36,184 --> 00:10:49,298
So in the discourse on Girima Ananda, who is a monk and he's very ill, and the Buddha knows about this and he tells Ananda to go and see him and gives him ten perceptions.

66
00:10:50,320 --> 00:10:53,203
Perception of impermanence, of not-self.

67
00:10:53,224 --> 00:10:59,931
Now here it's translated as ugliness, sometimes it's translated as repulsiveness.

68
00:11:01,008 --> 00:11:13,066
The drawbacks, giving up, fading away, cessation, dissatisfaction with the whole world, impermanence of all conditions and mindfulness of breathing.

69
00:11:13,846 --> 00:11:24,062
And we'll just concentrate on the business of the body and its foulness or ugliness or unpleasantness, maybe we should say.

70
00:11:25,054 --> 00:11:29,142
So interestingly enough, there are 31 parts numerated by the Buddha.

71
00:11:29,903 --> 00:11:47,215
In this body, there's head hair, body hair, nails, teeth, skin, flesh, sinews, bones, bone marrow, kidneys, heart, liver, diaphragm, spleen, lungs, intestines, bowels, undigested food, feces, bile.

72
00:11:47,635 --> 00:11:48,857
Oh, we had bile twice, have we?

73
00:11:48,898 --> 00:11:49,458
No.

74
00:11:49,438 --> 00:12:08,476
phlegm pus blood sweat fat tears grease saliva snot synovial fluid and urine that's quite a wonderful list interestingly and it's always i've always sort of wondered why but the brain isn't included

75
00:12:08,677 --> 00:12:32,962
and then i but it is when you do the mahayana list they they've added it and and the list sort of uh changes a little bit so you've got feces and then brain presumably saying that you're you might be a head or something but it seems as though the ancients didn't know what this excuse me this um

76
00:12:33,922 --> 00:12:58,495
know lump of fat or whatever it in the head was they thought it was part of the skull part of a cartilage or something it seems they had no idea that's that's where your thinking and imagining is manufactured now although i say that although we might be surprised by that because you know now we take this for granted uh you know when when you're thinking and imagining

77
00:12:59,960 --> 00:13:28,886
it's out there somewhere isn't it it's not although it's inside you it's it's sort of you wouldn't imagine it to come out of this lump of fat that's inside your head and uh i think in those days uh prior to our split our severe split between the body and mind people thought more from the heart often more more about what i feel what i understand rather than what i think and understand anyway

78
00:13:30,470 --> 00:13:40,802
What we're supposed to do, of course, is to bring the image of these in mind and just relate and just feel what our relationship is.

79
00:13:41,222 --> 00:13:44,767
Normally speaking, it's some form or some level of disgust.

80
00:13:45,828 --> 00:13:48,351
And to recognize that that's not necessary.

81
00:13:48,611 --> 00:13:54,438
That's, again, something to do with not really accepting our body as animal.

82
00:13:55,259 --> 00:13:57,743
We're here as animals as well.

83
00:13:57,789 --> 00:14:02,394
and not accepting that part of it is unpleasant.

84
00:14:02,755 --> 00:14:06,419
It doesn't smell nice for a start.

85
00:14:07,861 --> 00:14:10,904
And it's just recognizing it's a smell.

86
00:14:11,446 --> 00:14:23,679
And the disgust is not actually necessary at all, which is a measure of our delusion about how the body should be or how we imagine the body to be.

87
00:14:26,647 --> 00:14:33,687
So now, of course, the Buddha says what we do is to contemplate the drawbacks.

88
00:14:36,568 --> 00:14:59,725
This body has much suffering and many drawbacks, for this body is beset with many kinds of affliction, such as the following diseases of the eye, inner ear, nose, tongue, body, head, outer ear, mouth, teeth and lips, cough, asthma, catarrh, inflammation, fever, stomachache,

89
00:14:59,705 --> 00:15:19,350
fainting dysentery gastric pain cholera leprosy boils eczema tuberculosis epilepsy herpes itch scabs smallpox scabies hemorrhage diabetes piles pimples and ulcers

90
00:15:19,330 --> 00:15:25,618
Afflictions stemming from disorders of bile, phlegm, wind or their conjunction.

91
00:15:25,638 --> 00:15:34,708
Afflictions caused by change in the weather, by not taking care of ourselves, by over-exertion or as a result of past deeds.

92
00:15:35,230 --> 00:15:40,235
Cold, heat, hunger, thirst, defecation and urination.

93
00:15:40,956 --> 00:15:44,881
And so they meditate, observing the drawbacks of the body.

94
00:15:46,447 --> 00:16:04,827
the great old list isn't it he's not shy of you know listing these things at all is he so you know hits it on the nose you might say so uh these exercises are given us in order to undermine this relationship of attachment to the body

95
00:16:06,192 --> 00:16:12,318
Now, we have to ask ourselves, why do we form this relationship of attachment to the body?

96
00:16:12,359 --> 00:16:20,448
And for that, you have to go back a couple of steps to this idea of identity, which we're trying to constantly undermine.

97
00:16:21,230 --> 00:16:25,995
So this identity, this me, is seeking happiness, remember.

98
00:16:26,657 --> 00:16:28,278
It's just seeking it in the wrong place.

99
00:16:29,059 --> 00:16:35,827
And what it does by seeking happiness, it forms a relationship with what makes it happy.

100
00:16:35,807 --> 00:17:01,477
how do we define our happiness i would say for the most part it's how we feel you know i feel happy i feel comforted i feel i feel warm i feel beautiful i'm in love and etc etc so this happiness has a an anchor in the way we feel and that's what we're always chasing we're always chasing something that's going to make me feel good

101
00:17:02,149 --> 00:17:09,653
And that's where the problem lies because then everything that makes us feel good becomes something we depend upon.

102
00:17:10,675 --> 00:17:13,644
And when it's not there, that's when you get your grief and your

103
00:17:13,979 --> 00:17:42,281
and behind it sits your fear of loss and so on and so forth all the miseries come out of trying to seek some sort of permanent happiness through the body and the mistake that we can make of course is then not is then to a shoe to try and get away from all uh sensual pleasures well that that that just takes you into a very miserable place like a dry prune i mean that's no good at all so

104
00:17:42,700 --> 00:17:52,171
It's not a case of getting rid of sensual pleasures as such, but getting rid of that relationship and being aware of it, you see, being aware of it.

105
00:17:53,192 --> 00:18:06,446
And of course, that was the old reason for fasting, you know, and why Muslims also fast for one month every year is to, you know, to try and cut through this dependency we have on the sensual world for pleasure.

106
00:18:07,455 --> 00:18:14,366
That's what we used to do it for, you know, as Christians or I as a Catholic.

107
00:18:14,386 --> 00:18:16,971
During Lent you had to give something up, you see, your sweets.

108
00:18:17,633 --> 00:18:26,207
Well, there's a pain really, but the idea was to realize that you don't need sweets in order to be happy.

109
00:18:27,435 --> 00:18:44,179
So this verse, I've sort of built up a lot around it, but the basic message, of course, is the impermanence, the insubstantiality, and how not to be attracted by Mara's flowers.

110
00:18:45,172 --> 00:18:59,011
So I can only hope my words have been of some assistance, that they have not caused confusion and that by your devotion to practice you will be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

